{"id":"1810.13114","submitter":"Lu Guo","authors":"Lu Guo, Caiwan Shen, Chong Yu, Zhenji Wu","title":"Isotopic trends of quasifission and fusion-fission in the reactions\n  $^{48}$Ca+$^{239,244}$Pu","comments":"10 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. C 98, 064609 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevC.98.064609","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th nucl-ex","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Background: Quasifission and fusion-fission are primary mechanisms to prevent\nthe production of superheavy elements. The recent experimental measurements\nreveal that the fusion-evaporation cross section in the $3n$ reaction channel\nof $^{48}$Ca+$^{239}$Pu is 50 times lower than using $^{244}$Pu as target\nnucleus. However, the precise mechanisms of this remarkable isotopic dependence\nare not well understood.\n  Purpose: To understand the experimental observation of the rapid decrease of\nstability of superheavy nuclei as the neutron number decreases, the theoretical\nstudies of quasifission and fusion-fission in connection with experimental\nproduction for $Z$=114 flerovium isotopes are required to investigate the\npossible differences in reaction mechanisms induced by these two targets.\n  Methods: We propose an approach called TDHF+HIVAP to take into account both\nthe evolution of dinuclear system and the deexcitation of compound nucleus,\nwhich combines the microscopic time-dependent Hartree-Fock (TDHF) method for\nthe fusion and quasifission dynamics with the statistical evaporation model\nHIVAP for fusion-fission dynamics.\n  Results: ......The quantum shell effect displays a crucial role in both the\nquasifission and the fusion-fission processes. The quasifission is considerably\nreduced and the survival probability is enhanced around one order of magnitude\nin the reaction using $^{244}$Pu target as compared to the $^{239}$Pu case.\n  Conclusions: The studies by using TDHF+HIVAP method well account for the\nexperimental observation